05238nam a22008175i 9780812205138DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20112012pau    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979580779  a97808122051387 a10.9783/97808122051382doi  a(DE-B1597)449489  a(OCoLC)822017890  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 4aBP55 -- S46 2012eb 7aREL0370102bisacsh04a297.6351 aShoemaker, Stephen J., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut14aThe Death of a Prophet :bThe End of Muhammad's Life and the Beginnings of Islam /cStephen J. Shoemaker. 1aPhiladelphia : bUniversity of Pennsylvania Press, c[2011] 4c©2012  a1 online resource (416 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aDivinations: Rereading Late Ancient Religion00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tChapter 1. “A Prophet Has Appeared, Coming with the Saracens” -- tChapter 2. The End of Muhammad’s Life in Early Islamic Memory -- tChapter 3. The Beginnings of Islam and the End of Days -- tChapter 4. From Believers to Muslims, from Jerusalem to the Ḥijāz -- tConclusion: Jesus and Muhammad, the Apostle and the Apostles -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex -- tAcknowledgments0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe oldest Islamic biography of Muhammad, written in the mid-eighth century, relates that the prophet died at Medina in 632, while earlier and more numerous Jewish, Christian, Samaritan, and even Islamic sources indicate that Muhammad survived to lead the conquest of Palestine, beginning in 634-35. Although this discrepancy has been known for several decades, Stephen J. Shoemaker here writes the first systematic study of the various traditions.Using methods and perspectives borrowed from biblical studies, Shoemaker concludes that these reports of Muhammad's leadership during the Palestinian invasion likely preserve an early Islamic tradition that was later revised to meet the needs of a changing Islamic self-identity. Muhammad and his followers appear to have expected the world to end in the immediate future, perhaps even in their own lifetimes, Shoemaker contends. When the eschatological Hour failed to arrive on schedule and continued to be deferred to an ever more distant point, the meaning of Muhammad's message and the faith that he established needed to be fundamentally rethought by his early followers.The larger purpose of The Death of a Prophet exceeds the mere possibility of adjusting the date of Muhammad's death by a few years; far more important to Shoemaker are questions about the manner in which Islamic origins should be studied. The difference in the early sources affords an important opening through which to explore the nature of primitive Islam more broadly. Arguing for greater methodological unity between the study of Christian and Islamic origins, Shoemaker emphasizes the potential value of non-Islamic sources for reconstructing the history of formative Islam.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aIslamvHistoriography. 0aIslamxHistoriography. 0aIslamxHistory. 0aRELIGIONvIslamxHistory. 4aReligious Studies. 7aRELIGION / Islam / History.2bisacsh  aAncient Studies.  aHistory.  aReligion.  aReligious Studies.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Complete Collectionz978311041345808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn Press eBook Package Religionz978311041358808iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Pennsylvania Backlist eBook-Package 2000-2013z978311045954840uhttps://doi.org/10.9783/978081220513840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780812205138423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780812205138.jpg  a978-3-11-04134